Title: Alice's Adventures in Wonderland
Credit: Written by
Author: Lewis Carroll
Source: Adapted from the book by Lewis Carroll
Draft date: 7/20/2026

Notes: Period live-action Victorian fantasy; humans and talking animals share one stylized live-action medium. ALICE: about seven, fair hair, knee-length blue dress, white apron, striped stockings. WHITE RABBIT: white fur, pink eyes, waistcoat, pocket-watch. Recurring places keep identical heading names.

===

EXT. RIVER BANK - DAY

A hot summer afternoon. ALICE, about seven, fair hair half-loose, blue dress and white apron, sits beside her older SISTER on the grassy bank. The Sister reads a dense book without pictures. Alice peeps at the page, sighs, and flops back among the daisies.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Alice was beginning to get very tired of sitting by her sister on the bank, and of having nothing to do.

Alice eyes the daisies, weighing whether a daisy-chain is worth the trouble. She yawns, heavy with heat.

A WHITE RABBIT with pink eyes, neat waistcoat, and upright ears dashes close past her.

WHITE RABBIT
Oh dear! Oh dear! I shall be late!

Alice barely blinks — until the Rabbit draws a watch from its waistcoat-pocket, consults it, and hurries on.

Alice starts to her feet, burning with curiosity, and runs across the field after it.

EXT. HEDGE AND RABBIT-HOLE - DAY

The White Rabbit pops down a large rabbit-hole under the hedge.

Alice arrives just in time. Without a thought for getting out again, she goes down after it.

INT. RABBIT-HOLE TUNNEL - CONTINUOUS

The passage runs straight like a tunnel, then dips suddenly. Alice falls — not a drop, but a long, slow descent down a very deep well.

Cupboards and book-shelves line the sides; maps and pictures hang on pegs. As she drifts past, she takes a jar labelled ORANGE MARMALADE. Empty. She shelves it carefully in a cupboard rather than drop it.

ALICE
Well! After such a fall as this, I shall think nothing of tumbling down stairs! How brave they'll all think me at home! Why, I wouldn't say anything about it, even if I fell off the top of the house!

Down, down, down. Darkness above and below.

ALICE
I wonder how many miles I've fallen by this time? I must be getting somewhere near the centre of the earth. Let me see: that would be four thousand miles down, I think — yes, that's about the right distance — but then I wonder what Latitude or Longitude I've got to?

She considers, solemn.

ALICE
I wonder if I shall fall right through the earth! How funny it'll seem to come out among the people that walk with their heads downward! The Antipathies, I think — but I shall have to ask them what the name of the country is, you know. Please, Ma'am, is this New Zealand or Australia?

She tries a little curtsey in mid-air, skirts floating.

ALICE
And what an ignorant little girl she'll think me for asking! No, it'll never do to ask: perhaps I shall see it written up somewhere.

Still falling. She grows dreamy.

ALICE
Dinah'll miss me very much to-night, I should think! I hope they'll remember her saucer of milk at tea-time. Dinah my dear! I wish you were down here with me! There are no mice in the air, I'm afraid, but you might catch a bat, and that's very like a mouse, you know. But do cats eat bats, I wonder?

Her eyes half-close.

ALICE
(dozing)
Do cats eat bats? Do cats eat bats? Do bats eat cats?

She dreams she walks hand in hand with a cat, Dinah —

THUMP. THUMP. She lands on a heap of sticks and dry leaves. The fall is over.

INT. LONG PASSAGE - DAY

Alice is not hurt. She jumps up. Dark overhead; ahead, another long passage. The White Rabbit is still in sight, hurrying away.

She races after him like the wind.

WHITE RABBIT
(as he turns a corner)
Oh my ears and whiskers, how late it's getting!

Alice turns the corner — the Rabbit is gone.

INT. LONG LOW HALL - DAY

A long, low hall lit by a row of lamps hanging from the roof. Doors all round. Alice tries every one: all locked. She walks sadly down the middle.

A little three-legged table of solid glass stands alone. On it: a tiny golden key.

She tries the key on the doors — locks too large, or key too small. On a second circuit she finds a low curtain and, behind it, a little door about fifteen inches high. The golden key fits.

She opens the door onto a small passage no larger than a rat-hole. Beyond: the loveliest garden — bright flower-beds, cool fountains.

She kneels, longing, but cannot get even her head through.

ALICE
And even if my head would go through, it would be of very little use without my shoulders. Oh, how I wish I could shut up like a telescope! I think I could, if I only knew how to begin.

She goes back to the glass table. This time a little bottle stands on it — which certainly was not there before. A paper label round the neck: DRINK ME, in large letters.

ALICE
No, I'll look first, and see whether it's marked "poison" or not.

She examines it carefully. Not poison. She tastes — mixed flavour of cherry-tart, custard, pine-apple, roast turkey, toffee, and hot buttered toast — and finishes it off.

ALICE
What a curious feeling! I must be shutting up like a telescope.

She shrinks to ten inches high. Her face brightens — right size for the garden door. She waits, nervous, in case she goes out altogether like a candle.

Nothing more happens. She runs to the door — and has forgotten the golden key. Back at the table she cannot reach it; the glass top shows the key plainly. She tries to climb a slippery leg, fails, sits down and cries.

ALICE
(to herself, sharply)
Come, there's no use in crying like that! I advise you to leave off this minute!

She sniffs, scolding herself, then notices a little glass box under the table. Inside: a very small cake with EAT ME marked in currants.

ALICE
Well, I'll eat it, and if it makes me grow larger, I can reach the key; and if it makes me grow smaller, I can creep under the door; so either way I'll get into the garden, and I don't care which happens!

She eats a bit, hand on her head.

ALICE
Which way? Which way?

She stays the same size — dull, almost. She finishes the cake.

INT. LONG LOW HALL - MOMENTS LATER

ALICE
Curiouser and curiouser!

She shoots upward, opening out like the largest telescope.

ALICE
Now I'm opening out like the largest telescope that ever was! Good-bye, feet!

Her feet seem almost out of sight.

ALICE
Oh, my poor little feet, I wonder who will put on your shoes and stockings for you now, dears? I'm sure I shan't be able! I shall be a great deal too far off to trouble myself about you: you must manage the best way you can — but I must be kind to them, or perhaps they won't walk the way I want to go! Let me see: I'll give them a new pair of boots every Christmas.

She plans the directions aloud, half laughing at herself.

ALICE
They must go by the carrier — and how funny it'll seem, sending presents to one's own feet! Alice's Right Foot, Esq., Hearthrug, near the Fender, with Alice's love. Oh dear, what nonsense I'm talking!

Her head strikes the roof of the hall. She is more than nine feet high. She snatches the little golden key and hurries to the garden door.

Lying on her side, she can just look through with one eye. Getting through is hopeless. She sits and cries again — gallons of tears — until a large pool spreads round her, about four inches deep, half down the hall.

ALICE
You ought to be ashamed of yourself, a great girl like you, to go on crying in this way! Stop this moment, I tell you!

She cries on all the same.

A little pattering of feet. She dries her eyes. The White Rabbit returns, splendidly dressed, white kid gloves in one hand, a large fan in the other, trotting in a great hurry.

WHITE RABBIT
Oh! the Duchess, the Duchess! Oh! won't she be savage if I've kept her waiting!

Alice, desperate, speaks in a low timid voice as he comes near.

ALICE
If you please, sir —

The Rabbit starts violently, drops the gloves and fan, and scurries into the darkness.

Alice picks up the fan and gloves. The hall is very hot; she fans herself as she talks.

ALICE
Dear, dear! How queer everything is to-day! And yesterday things went on just as usual. I wonder if I've been changed in the night? Let me think: was I the same when I got up this morning? I almost think I can remember feeling a little different. But if I'm not the same, the next question is, Who in the world am I? Ah, that's the great puzzle!

She ticks off children she knows.

ALICE
I'm sure I'm not Ada, for her hair goes in such long ringlets, and mine doesn't go in ringlets at all; and I'm sure I can't be Mabel, for I know all sorts of things, and she, oh! she knows such a very little! Besides, she's she, and I'm I, and — oh dear, how puzzling it all is! I'll try if I know all the things I used to know. Let me see: four times five is twelve, and four times six is thirteen, and four times seven is — oh dear! I shall never get to twenty at that rate! However, the Multiplication Table doesn't signify: let's try Geography. London is the capital of Paris, and Paris is the capital of Rome, and Rome — no, that's all wrong, I'm certain! I must have been changed for Mabel! I'll try and say "How doth the little —"

She crosses her hands on her lap like lessons. Her voice comes hoarse and strange.

ALICE
How doth the little crocodile
Improve his shining tail,
And pour the waters of the Nile
On every golden scale!

How cheerfully he seems to grin,
How neatly spread his claws,
And welcome little fishes in
With gently smiling jaws!

ALICE
I'm sure those are not the right words.

Tears again.

ALICE
I must be Mabel after all, and I shall have to go and live in that poky little house, and have next to no toys to play with, and oh! ever so many lessons to learn! No, I've made up my mind about it; if I'm Mabel, I'll stay down here! It'll be no use their putting their heads down and saying "Come up again, dear!" I shall only look up and say "Who am I then? Tell me that first, and then, if I like being that person, I'll come up: if not, I'll stay down here till I'm somebody else" — but, oh dear!

A sudden burst of tears.

ALICE
I do wish they would put their heads down! I am so very tired of being all alone here!

She looks down at her hands — one of the Rabbit's little white kid gloves is on. She is shrinking.

ALICE
How can I have done that? I must be growing small again.

She measures herself by the table: about two feet, and still shrinking. The fan is the cause. She drops it just in time.

ALICE
That was a narrow escape! And now for the garden!

She runs to the little door — shut again; the golden key lies on the glass table as before.

ALICE
And things are worse than ever, for I never was so small as this before, never! And I declare it's too bad, that it is!

Her foot slips — splash — she is up to her chin in salt water.

INT. POOL OF TEARS - CONTINUOUS

Alice swims, at first thinking it the sea.

ALICE
And in that case I can go back by railway.

She realizes: the pool of tears she wept when nine feet high.

ALICE
I wish I hadn't cried so much! I shall be punished for it now, I suppose, by being drowned in my own tears! That will be a queer thing, to be sure! However, everything is queer to-day.

Something splashes nearby. She swims nearer — not a walrus or hippopotamus, but a MOUSE, small as she is now, slipped in like herself.

ALICE
O Mouse, do you know the way out of this pool? I am very tired of swimming about here, O Mouse!

The Mouse looks at her inquisitively, seems to wink, says nothing.

ALICE
(to herself)
Perhaps it doesn't understand English. I daresay it's a French mouse, come over with William the Conqueror.

ALICE
Ou est ma chatte?

The Mouse leaps, quivering with fright.

ALICE
Oh, I beg your pardon! I quite forgot you didn't like cats.

THE MOUSE
(shrill, passionate)
Not like cats! Would you like cats if you were me?

ALICE
(soothing)
Well, perhaps not: don't be angry about it. And yet I wish I could show you our cat Dinah: I think you'd take a fancy to cats if you could only see her. She is such a dear quiet thing, and she sits purring so nicely by the fire, licking her paws and washing her face — and she is such a nice soft thing to nurse — and she's such a capital one for catching mice — oh, I beg your pardon!

The Mouse bristles all over.

ALICE
We won't talk about her any more if you'd rather not.

THE MOUSE
(trembling to the end of his tail)
We indeed! As if I would talk on such a subject! Our family always hated cats: nasty, low, vulgar things! Don't let me hear the name again!

ALICE
I won't indeed! Are you — are you fond — of — of dogs?

No answer. She presses on eagerly.

ALICE
There is such a nice little dog near our house I should like to show you! A little bright-eyed terrier, you know, with oh, such long curly brown hair! And it'll fetch things when you throw them, and it'll sit up and beg for its dinner, and all sorts of things — I can't remember half of them — and it belongs to a farmer, you know, and he says it's so useful, it's worth a hundred pounds! He says it kills all the rats and — oh dear!

The Mouse swims away hard, making a commotion.

ALICE
(softly after it)
Mouse dear! Do come back again, and we won't talk about cats or dogs either, if you don't like them!

The Mouse turns and swims slowly back, face pale with passion.

THE MOUSE
(low, trembling)
Let us get to the shore, and then I'll tell you my history, and you'll understand why it is I hate cats and dogs.

The pool grows crowded: a DUCK, a DODO, a LORY, an EAGLET, and other curious creatures, all fallen in. Alice leads; the whole party swims for shore.

EXT. BANK OF THE POOL - DAY

A queer-looking party assembles — birds with draggled feathers, animals with fur clinging close, all dripping, cross, and uncomfortable.

They consult how to get dry. Alice finds herself talking familiarly with them. She argues with the Lory.

THE LORY
I am older than you, and must know better.

Alice will not allow it without knowing the Lory's age. The Lory refuses. Stalemate.

The Mouse, a person of authority among them, calls out.

THE MOUSE
Sit down, all of you, and listen to me! I'll soon make you dry enough!

They sit in a large ring, Mouse in the middle. Alice watches anxiously, sure of a bad cold if she stays wet.

THE MOUSE
(with an important air)
Ahem! Are you all ready? This is the driest thing I know. Silence all round, if you please! "William the Conqueror, whose cause was favoured by the pope, was soon submitted to by the English, who wanted leaders, and had been of late much accustomed to usurpation and conquest. Edwin and Morcar, the earls of Mercia and Northumbria —"

THE LORY
(with a shiver)
Ugh!

THE MOUSE
(frowning, polite)
I beg your pardon! Did you speak?

THE LORY
(hastily)
Not I!

THE MOUSE
I thought you did. — I proceed. "Edwin and Morcar, the earls of Mercia and Northumbria, declared for him: and even Stigand, the patriotic archbishop of Canterbury, found it advisable —"

THE DUCK
Found what?

THE MOUSE
(crossly)
Found it, of course you know what "it" means.

THE DUCK
I know what "it" means well enough, when I find a thing: it's generally a frog or a worm. The question is, what did the archbishop find?

The Mouse will not stand this. It stands up and says in a trembling voice —

THE MOUSE
I proceed. "Found it advisable to go with Edgar Atheling to meet William and offer him the crown. William's conduct at first was moderate. But the insolence of his Normans —" How are you getting on now, my dear?

It turns to Alice as it speaks.

ALICE
As wet as ever. It doesn't seem to dry me at all.

THE DODO
In that case, I move that the meeting adjourn, for the immediate adoption of more energetic remedies —

THE EAGLET
Speak English! I don't know the meaning of half those long words, and, what's more, I don't believe you do either!

The Eaglet bends down its head to hide a smile; some of the other birds titter.

THE DODO
I only meant to say that the best thing to get us dry would be a Caucus-race.

ALICE
What is a Caucus-race?

THE DODO
Why, the best way to explain it is to do it.

The Dodo marks out a race-course in a sort of circle. The party places itself all along the course, here and there. There is no "One, two, three, and away," but they begin running when they like, and leave off when they like, so that it is not easy to know when the race is over.

After half an hour or so they are quite dry again. The Dodo calls out —

THE DODO
The race is over!

They crowd round, panting, asking who has won.

THE DODO
(after long thought, solemnly)
Everybody has won, and all must have prizes.

ALL
But who is to give the prizes?

THE DODO
(pointing to Alice)
Why, she, of course.

Alice has no idea what to do. She puts her hand in her pocket and pulls out a box of comfits (luckily the salt water has not got into it) and hands them round as prizes. There is exactly one a-piece all round.

ALL
But she must have a prize herself, you know.

THE DODO
Of course. What else have you got in your pocket?

ALICE
Only a thimble.

THE DODO
Hand it over here.

The Dodo receives the thimble solemnly, then presents it back to Alice, saying —

THE DODO
We beg your acceptance of this elegant thimble.

They all cheer. Alice looks as solemn as she can.

The party settles down again. The Mouse is called upon for its history.

THE MOUSE
Mine is a long and a sad tale!

ALICE
(looking at the Mouse's tail)
It is a long tail, certainly, but why do you call it sad?

THE MOUSE
It is a long tail, certainly — but why do you call it sad?

The Mouse tells its tale of Fury and the Mouse, growing angrier as Alice's attention wanders to the shape of the tale on the ground.

THE MOUSE
You are not attending!

ALICE
I beg your pardon. You had got to the fifth bend, I think?

THE MOUSE
I had not!

ALICE
A knot! Oh, do let me help to undo it!

THE MOUSE
I shall do nothing of the sort. You insult me by talking such nonsense!

The Mouse gets up and walks away.

ALICE
Please come back and finish your story!

OTHERS
Yes, please do!

But the Mouse only shakes its head impatiently and walks a little quicker.

THE LORY
I wish I had our Dinah here, I know I do!

Alice eagerly describes Dinah: a capital hand at catching mice and a terror to birds. The birds and animals move off at once. Soon Alice is left alone.

ALICE
I wish I hadn't mentioned Dinah! Nobody seems to like her, down here, and I'm sure she's the best cat in the world!

Her eyes fill with tears again.

A little pattering of footsteps. Alice looks up eagerly.

The WHITE RABBIT trots slowly back, looking anxiously about, as if he has lost something.

WHITE RABBIT
The Duchess! The Duchess! Oh my dear paws! Oh my fur and whiskers! She'll get me executed, as sure as ferrets are ferrets! Where CAN I have dropped them, I wonder?

Alice guesses at once: the fan and the white kid gloves. She hunts about good-naturedly. Nothing. The great hall, the glass table, the little door — all vanished. The bank and wood have changed since the swim.

The Rabbit notices her and calls out in an angry tone.

WHITE RABBIT
Why, Mary Ann, what ARE you doing out here? Run home this moment, and fetch me a pair of gloves and a fan! Quick, now!

Alice is so frightened she runs off at once in the direction he points, without explaining the mistake.

ALICE
(to herself, running)
He took me for his housemaid. How surprised he'll be when he finds out who I am! But I'd better take him his fan and gloves — that is, if I can find them.

EXT. WHITE RABBIT'S HOUSE - DAY

A neat little house. On the door, a bright brass plate: W. RABBIT.

Alice goes in without knocking.

INT. WHITE RABBIT'S HOUSE - STAIRS - DAY

She hurries upstairs in great fear of meeting the real Mary Ann.

ALICE
(to herself)
How queer it seems to be going messages for a rabbit! I suppose Dinah'll be sending me on messages next!

INT. WHITE RABBIT'S TIDY LITTLE ROOM - DAY

A tidy little room. A table in the window. On it: a fan and two or three pairs of tiny white kid gloves.

Alice takes up the fan and a pair of gloves. She is just going to leave when her eye falls on a little bottle near the looking-glass. No label this time. She uncorks it and puts it to her lips.

ALICE
(to herself)
I know SOMETHING interesting is sure to happen whenever I eat or drink anything; so I'll just see what this bottle does. I do hope it'll make me grow large again, for really I'm quite tired of being such a tiny little thing!

Before she has drunk half the bottle, her head presses against the ceiling. She stoops to save her neck.

ALICE
That's quite enough — I hope I shan't grow any more — As it is, I can't get out at the door — I do wish I hadn't drunk quite so much!

Too late. She goes on growing. She kneels on the floor. Then there is not room even for that. She lies down with one elbow against the door, the other arm curled round her head.

Still growing. As a last resource she puts one arm out of the window and one foot up the chimney.

ALICE
Now I can do no more, whatever happens. What WILL become of me?

The bottle has had its full effect. She grows no larger — still very uncomfortable, wedged in the little room.

ALICE
(unhappy, to herself)
It was much pleasanter at home, when one wasn't always growing larger and smaller, and being ordered about by mice and rabbits. I almost wish I hadn't gone down that rabbit-hole — and yet — and yet — it's rather curious, you know, this sort of life! I do wonder what CAN have happened to me! When I used to read fairy-tales, I fancied that kind of thing never happened, and now here I am in the middle of one! There ought to be a book written about me, that there ought! And when I grow up, I'll write one — but I'm grown up now... at least there's no room to grow up any more HERE.

ALICE
(answering herself)
But then, shall I NEVER get any older than I am now? That'll be a comfort, one way — never to be an old woman — but then — always to have lessons to learn! Oh, I shouldn't like THAT!

ALICE
(as the other side)
Oh, you foolish Alice! How can you learn lessons in here? Why, there's hardly room for YOU, and no room at all for any lesson-books!

A voice outside. She stops to listen.

WHITE RABBIT (O.S.)
Mary Ann! Mary Ann! Fetch me my gloves this moment!

A little pattering of feet on the stairs. Alice trembles till she shakes the house.

The Rabbit tries the door. It opens inwards; her elbow is pressed hard against it. Failure.

WHITE RABBIT (O.S.)
Then I'll go round and get in at the window.

ALICE
(to herself)
THAT you won't.

She waits till she fancies she hears him just under the window, then suddenly spreads out her hand and snatches in the air.

A little shriek. A fall. A crash of broken glass.

ALICE
(concluding)
A cucumber-frame, or something of the sort.

EXT. WHITE RABBIT'S HOUSE - GARDEN - DAY

WHITE RABBIT, dusty and furious among shattered glass of a cucumber-frame.

WHITE RABBIT
Pat! Pat! Where are you?

PAT, a gardener in rough clothes, Irish brogue, pops up with a spade.

PAT
Sure then I'm here! Digging for apples, yer honour!

WHITE RABBIT
(angrily)
Digging for apples, indeed! Here! Come and help me out of THIS!

More broken glass as Pat hauls him free.

WHITE RABBIT
Now tell me, Pat, what's that in the window?

PAT
Sure, it's an arm, yer honour!

WHITE RABBIT
An arm, you goose! Who ever saw one that size? Why, it fills the whole window!

PAT
Sure, it does, yer honour: but it's an arm for all that.

WHITE RABBIT
Well, it's got no business there, at any rate: go and take it away!

Long silence. Whispers.

PAT
(whispering)
Sure, I don't like it, yer honour, at all, at all!

WHITE RABBIT
(whispering)
Do as I tell you, you coward!

INT. WHITE RABBIT'S TIDY LITTLE ROOM - DAY

Alice spreads her hand again and snatches.

EXT. WHITE RABBIT'S HOUSE - GARDEN - DAY

TWO little shrieks. More broken glass. Pat and the Rabbit scramble back.

ALICE (O.S.)
What a number of cucumber-frames there must be! I wonder what they'll do next! As for pulling me out of the window, I only wish they COULD! I'm sure I don't want to stay in here any longer!

A rumbling of little cartwheels. Many VOICES talking together. Ladders. A rope. Little animals and birds gather — among them BILL, a poor little LIZARD.

VOICES
Where's the other ladder? — Bill! fetch it here, lad! — Here, put 'em up at this corner — No, tie 'em together first — Will the roof bear? — Mind that loose slate — Oh, it's coming down! Heads below!

A loud crash. A slate smashes.

VOICES
Now, who did that? — It was Bill, I fancy — Who's to go down the chimney? — Nay, I shan't! YOU do it! — Bill's to go down — Here, Bill! the master says you're to go down the chimney!

INT. WHITE RABBIT'S TIDY LITTLE ROOM - DAY

Alice's foot is up the chimney. She draws it as far down as she can.

ALICE
(to herself)
Oh! So Bill's got to come down the chimney, has he? Shy, they seem to put everything upon Bill! I wouldn't be in Bill's place for a good deal: this fireplace is narrow, to be sure; but I THINK I can kick a little!

Scratching and scrambling in the chimney close above her foot — a little animal.

ALICE
This is Bill.

She gives one sharp kick.

EXT. WHITE RABBIT'S HOUSE - GARDEN - DAY

GENERAL CHORUS
There goes Bill!

Bill the Lizard shoots out of the chimney like a sky-rocket, arcs over the garden, and comes down among the crowd by the hedge.

WHITE RABBIT
Catch him, you by the hedge!

Silence — then confusion. Two GUINEA-PIGS hold Bill up. Someone tips a bottle toward his mouth.

VOICES
Hold up his head — Brandy now — Don't choke him — How was it, old fellow? What happened to you?

BILL
(feeble, squeaking)
Well, I hardly know — No more, thank ye; I'm better now — but I'm a deal too flustered to tell you — all I know is, something comes at me like a Jack-in-the-box, and up I goes like a sky-rocket!

VOICES
So you did, old fellow!

WHITE RABBIT
We must burn the house down!

ALICE (O.S.)
(as loud as she can)
If you do, I'll set Dinah at you!

Dead silence instantly.

INT. WHITE RABBIT'S TIDY LITTLE ROOM - DAY

ALICE
(to herself)
I wonder what they WILL do next! If they had any sense, they'd take the roof off.

EXT. WHITE RABBIT'S HOUSE - GARDEN - DAY

After a minute or two they move about again.

WHITE RABBIT
A barrowful will do, to begin with.

A barrow. Little animals load pebbles. A shower of little pebbles rattles in at the window.

INT. WHITE RABBIT'S TIDY LITTLE ROOM - DAY

Some pebbles hit Alice in the face.

ALICE
(to herself)
I'll put a stop to this.

ALICE
(shouting)
You'd better not do that again!

Another dead silence outside.

Alice notices with surprise: the pebbles on the floor are all turning into little cakes.

ALICE
(to herself)
If I eat one of these cakes, it's sure to make SOME change in my size; and as it can't possibly make me larger, it must make me smaller, I suppose.

She swallows one of the cakes. She begins shrinking directly.

As soon as she is small enough to get through the door, she runs out.

EXT. WHITE RABBIT'S HOUSE - GARDEN - DAY

A crowd of little animals and birds waits outside. Bill the Lizard is in the middle, held up by two guinea-pigs.

They all make a rush at Alice the moment she appears. She runs off as hard as she can.

EXT. THICK WOOD - DAY

Alice runs until she is safe among the trees.

ALICE
(to herself, wandering)
The first thing I've got to do is to grow to my right size again; and the second thing is to find my way into that lovely garden. I think that will be the best plan.

An excellent plan — only she has not the smallest idea how to set about it. She peers anxiously among the trees.

A little sharp bark just over her head. She looks up in a great hurry.

An ENORMOUS PUPPY looks down at her with large round eyes, feebly stretching out one paw, trying to touch her. Compared to tiny Alice, it is vast.

ALICE
(coaxing, terrified)
Poor little thing!

She tries hard to whistle. She is terribly frightened it might be hungry.

Hardly knowing what she does, she picks up a little bit of stick and holds it out.

The puppy jumps into the air off all its feet at once, with a yelp of delight, rushes at the stick, and makes believe to worry it.

Alice dodges behind a great thistle to keep from being run over. The moment she appears on the other side, the puppy makes another rush and tumbles head over heels in its hurry.

Like a game of play with a cart-horse. She expects every moment to be trampled. She runs round the thistle again.

The puppy begins a series of short charges at the stick — a very little way forwards, a long way back — barking hoarsely all the while — till at last it sits down a good way off, panting, tongue hanging out, great eyes half shut.

Alice seizes the chance. She sets off at once and runs till she is quite tired and out of breath, and the puppy's bark sounds quite faint in the distance.

EXT. WOOD - BUTTERCUP CLEARING - DAY

Alice leans against a buttercup to rest, and fans herself with one of the leaves. She is still only a few inches high.

ALICE
And yet what a dear little puppy it was! I should have liked teaching it tricks very much, if — if I'd only been the right size to do it! Oh dear! I'd nearly forgotten that I've got to grow up again! Let me see — how IS it to be managed? I suppose I ought to eat or drink something or other; but the great question is, what?

She looks all round at the flowers and blades of grass. Nothing that looks like the right thing.

A large mushroom grows near her, about the same height as herself. She looks under it, on both sides, behind it — then stretches up on tiptoe and peeps over the edge.

Her eyes meet those of a large CATERPILLAR, sitting on the top with its arms folded, quietly smoking a long hookah, taking not the smallest notice of her.

EXT. WOOD - MUSHROOM - DAY

The CATERPILLAR — blue-green, exactly three inches high, languid — and Alice look at each other for some time in silence.

At last the Caterpillar takes the hookah out of its mouth and addresses her in a sleepy voice.

CATERPILLAR
Who are YOU?

ALICE
(shyly)
I — I hardly know, sir, just at present — at least I know who I WAS when I got up this morning, but I think I must have been changed several times since then.

CATERPILLAR
(sternly)
What do you mean by that? Explain yourself!

ALICE
I can't explain MYSELF, I'm afraid, sir, because I'm not myself, you see.

CATERPILLAR
I don't see.

ALICE
(very politely)
I'm afraid I can't put it more clearly, for I can't understand it myself to begin with; and being so many different sizes in a day is very confusing.

CATERPILLAR
It isn't.

ALICE
Well, perhaps you haven't found it so yet; but when you have to turn into a chrysalis — you will some day, you know — and then after that into a butterfly, I should think you'll feel it a little queer, won't you?

CATERPILLAR
Not a bit.

ALICE
Well, perhaps your feelings may be different; all I know is, it would feel very queer to ME.

CATERPILLAR
(contemptuously)
You! Who are YOU?

Back to the beginning. Alice draws herself up, a little irritated.

ALICE
(very gravely)
I think you ought to tell me who YOU are, first.

CATERPILLAR
Why?

Alice cannot think of any good reason. The Caterpillar seems in a VERY unpleasant state of mind. She turns away.

CATERPILLAR
Come back! I've something important to say!

Alice turns and comes back.

CATERPILLAR
Keep your temper.

ALICE
(swallowing her anger)
Is that all?

CATERPILLAR
No.

Alice waits. For some minutes the Caterpillar puffs away without speaking. At last it unfolds its arms, takes the hookah out again.

CATERPILLAR
So you think you're changed, do you?

ALICE
I'm afraid I am, sir. I can't remember things as I used — and I don't keep the same size for ten minutes together!

CATERPILLAR
Can't remember WHAT things?

ALICE
(melancholy)
Well, I've tried to say "HOW DOTH THE LITTLE BUSY BEE," but it all came different!

CATERPILLAR
Repeat, "YOU ARE OLD, FATHER WILLIAM."

Alice folds her hands and begins.

ALICE
"You are old, Father William," the young man said,
"And your hair has become very white;
And yet you incessantly stand on your head —
Do you think, at your age, it is right?"

"In my youth," Father William replied to his son,
"I feared it might injure the brain;
But, now that I'm perfectly sure I have none,
Why, I do it again and again."

"You are old," said the youth, "as I mentioned before,
And have grown most uncommonly fat;
Yet you turned a back-somersault in at the door —
Pray, what is the reason of that?"

"In my youth," said the sage, as he shook his grey locks,
"I kept all my limbs very supple
By the use of this ointment — one shilling the box —
Allow me to sell you a couple?"

"You are old," said the youth, "and your jaws are too weak
For anything tougher than suet;
Yet you finished the goose, with the bones and the beak —
Pray, how did you manage to do it?"

"In my youth," said his father, "I took to the law,
And argued each case with my wife;
And the muscular strength, which it gave to my jaw,
Has lasted the rest of my life."

"You are old," said the youth, "one would hardly suppose
That your eye was as steady as ever;
Yet you balanced an eel on the end of your nose —
What made you so awfully clever?"

"I have answered three questions, and that is enough,"
Said his father; "don't give yourself airs!
Do you think I can listen all day to such stuff?
Be off, or I'll kick you down stairs!"

CATERPILLAR
That is not said right.

ALICE
Not quite right, I'm afraid. Some of the words have got altered.

CATERPILLAR
It is wrong from beginning to end.

The Caterpillar is silent for some minutes. Alice waits and waits.

CATERPILLAR
What size do you want to be?

ALICE
Oh, I'm not particular as to size; only one doesn't like changing so often, you know.

CATERPILLAR
I don't know.

Alice says nothing. She has never been so much contradicted in her life before.

CATERPILLAR
Are you content now?

ALICE
Well, I should like to be a little larger, sir, if you wouldn't mind. Three inches is such a wretched height to be.

CATERPILLAR
It is a very good height indeed!

ALICE
But I'm not used to it!

CATERPILLAR
You'll get used to it in time.

It puts the hookah into its mouth and begins smoking again. Alice waits patiently until it chooses to speak.

CATERPILLAR
(taking the hookah out, yawning)
One side will make you grow taller, and the other side will make you grow shorter.

ALICE
One side of what? The other side of what?

CATERPILLAR
Of the mushroom.

It crawls away into the grass, merely remarking as it goes —

CATERPILLAR
One side will make you grow taller, and the other side will make you grow shorter.

Alice stands looking thoughtfully at the mushroom, trying to make out which are the two sides of it. As it is perfectly round, she finds this a difficult question.

At last she stretches her arms round it as far as they will go, and breaks off a bit of the edge with each hand.

ALICE
And now which is which?

She nibbles a little of the right-hand bit. The next moment she feels a violent blow underneath her chin: it has struck her foot!

She is a good deal frightened by this very sudden change, but she feels that there is no time to be lost, as she is shrinking rapidly; so she sets to work at once to eat some of the other bit.

Her chin is pressed so closely against her foot that there is hardly room to open her mouth; but she does it at last, and manages to swallow a morsel of the left-hand bit.

EXT. WOOD - NEAR MUSHROOM - DAY

Alice's head frees itself. She is delighted — until she finds her shoulders gone; all she can see when she looks down is an immense length of neck, rising like a stalk out of a sea of green leaves far below.

ALICE
(surprised)
What can all that green stuff be? And where have my shoulders got to? And oh, my poor hands, how is it I can't see you?

She is delighted to find that her neck will bend about easily in any direction, like a serpent. She has just succeeded in curving it down into a graceful zigzag and is going to dive in among the leaves, when a sharp hiss makes her draw back in a hurry.

A large PIGEON has flown into her face, beating her violently with its wings.

PIGEON
Serpent!

ALICE
I'm not a serpent! Let me alone!

PIGEON
Serpent, I say again! I've tried every way, and nothing seems to suit them!

ALICE
I haven't the least idea what you're talking about.

PIGEON
I've tried the roots of trees, and I've tried banks, and I've tried hedges; but those serpents! There's no pleasing them!

Alice is more and more puzzled.

PIGEON
As if it wasn't trouble enough hatching the eggs, but I must be on the look-out for serpents night and day! Why, I haven't had a wink of sleep these three weeks!

ALICE
I'm very sorry you've been annoyed.

PIGEON
And just as I'd taken the highest tree in the wood, and just as I was thinking I should be free of them at last, they must needs come wriggling down from the sky! Ugh, Serpent!

ALICE
But I'm not a serpent, I tell you! I'm a — I'm a —

PIGEON
Well! What are you? I can see you're trying to invent something!

ALICE
I — I'm a little girl.

PIGEON
(in a tone of the deepest contempt)
A likely story indeed! I've seen a good many little girls in my time, but never one with such a neck as that! No, no! You're a serpent; and there's no use denying it. I suppose you'll be telling me next that you never tasted an egg!

ALICE
I have tasted eggs, certainly; but little girls eat eggs quite as much as serpents do, you know.

PIGEON
I don't believe it. But if they do, why then they're a kind of serpent, that's all I can say.

This is such a new idea to Alice that she is quite silent for a minute or two.

PIGEON
You're looking for eggs, I know that well enough; and what does it matter to me whether you're a little girl or a serpent?

ALICE
It matters a good deal to me; but I'm not looking for eggs, as it happens; and if I was, I shouldn't want yours: I don't like them raw.

PIGEON
Well, be off, then!

Alice crouches down among the trees as well as she can, for her neck keeps getting entangled among the branches. Every now and then she has to stop and untwist it.

After a while she remembers she still holds the pieces of mushroom. She sets to work very carefully, nibbling first at one and then at the other, and growing sometimes taller and sometimes shorter, until she has brought herself down to her usual height.

ALICE
(to herself)
Come, there's half my plan done now! How puzzling all these changes are! I'm never sure what I'm going to be, from one minute to another! However, I've got back to my right size: the next thing is, to get into that beautiful garden — how is that to be done, I wonder?

As she says this, she comes suddenly upon an open place, with a little house in it about four feet high.

ALICE
Whoever lives there, it'll never do to come upon them this size: why, I should frighten them out of their wits!

She nibbles at the right-hand bit again, and does not venture to go near the house till she has brought herself down to nine inches high.

EXT. DUCHESS'S HOUSE - DAY

Alice stands before the door, wondering what to do next, when suddenly a footman in livery comes running out of the wood — the face of a fish, powdered hair drawn into a bag — and raps loudly at the door with his knuckles.

It is opened by another FOOTMAN with a round face and large eyes like a frog. Both have powdered hair curled all round their heads. Alice watches with great curiosity.

The Fish-Footman produces from under his arm a great letter, nearly as large as himself, and hands it over.

FISH-FOOTMAN
For the Duchess. An invitation from the Queen to play croquet.

The Frog-Footman repeats, in the same solemn tone, only changing the order of the words —

FROG-FOOTMAN
From the Queen. An invitation for the Duchess to play croquet.

They both bow low, and their curls get entangled together. Alice laughs so much she has to run back into the wood.

When she comes back, the Fish-Footman is gone, and the other is sitting on the ground near the door, staring stupidly up into the sky.

Alice goes timidly up to the door and knocks.

FROG-FOOTMAN
There's no sort of use in knocking, and that for two reasons. First, because I'm on the same side of the door as you are; secondly, because they're making such a noise inside, no one could possibly hear you.

And certainly there is a most extraordinary noise going on within — a constant howling and sneezing, and every now and then a great crash, as if a dish or kettle has been broken to pieces.

ALICE
Please, then, how am I to get in?

FROG-FOOTMAN
There might be some sense in your knocking if we had the door between us. For instance, if you were inside, you might knock, and I could let you out, you know.

He is looking up into the sky all the time he is speaking. Alice grows impatient.

ALICE
But what am I to do?

FROG-FOOTMAN
Anything you like.

ALICE
How am I to get in?

FROG-FOOTMAN
Are you to get in at all? That's the first question, you know.

It is clearly useless speaking to him. Alice opens the door and goes in.

INT. DUCHESS'S KITCHEN - DAY

A large kitchen, full of smoke from one end to the other. The DUCHESS sits on a three-legged stool in the middle, nursing a BABY; the COOK leans over the fire, stirring a large cauldron of soup.

The air is full of pepper. Even the Duchess sneezes occasionally; as for the baby, it is sneezing and howling alternately without a moment's pause. The only things that do not sneeze are the cook, and a large CHESHIRE CAT, which sits on the hearth and grins from ear to ear.

ALICE
(to herself)
There's certainly too much pepper in that soup!

She says it aloud, half to herself.

The Duchess only scowls. The cook takes no notice.

ALICE
Please would you tell me why your cat grins like that?

DUCHESS
It's a Cheshire cat, and that's why. Pig!

She says the last word with such sudden violence that Alice jumps; but she sees at once it is addressed to the baby, not to her.

ALICE
I didn't know that Cheshire cats always grinned; in fact, I didn't know that cats could grin.

DUCHESS
They all can, and most of 'em do.

ALICE
I don't know of any that do.

DUCHESS
You don't know much, and that's a fact.

Alice does not at all like the tone of this remark, and thinks it would be as well to introduce some other subject of conversation. While she is trying to fix on one, the cook takes the cauldron of soup off the fire, and at once sets to work throwing everything within her reach at the Duchess and the baby — the fire-irons first; then saucepans, plates, and dishes.

The Duchess takes no notice, even when they hit her. The baby is howling so that Alice can hardly hear the words.

DUCHESS
(to Alice)
If everybody minded their own business, the world would go round a deal faster than it does.

ALICE
Which would not be an advantage. Just think what work it would make with the day and night! You see the earth takes twenty-four hours to turn round on its axis —

DUCHESS
Talking of axes, chop off her head!

Alice glances rather anxiously at the cook, to see if she means to take the hint; but the cook is busily stirring the soup, and seems not to be listening.

DUCHESS
(singing to the baby, giving it a violent shake at the end of every line)
Speak roughly to your little boy,
And beat him when he sneezes:
He only does it to annoy,
Because he knows it teases.

CHORUS
(cook and baby)
Wow! wow! wow!

DUCHESS
I speak severely to my boy,
I beat him when he sneezes;
For he can thoroughly enjoy
The pepper when he pleases!

CHORUS
Wow! wow! wow!

DUCHESS
Here! You may nurse it a bit, if you like!

She flings the baby at Alice. Alice catches it hastily.

DUCHESS
I must go and get ready to play croquet with the Queen.

She hurries out of the room. The cook throws a frying-pan after her as she goes, but it just misses.

Alice is a little alarmed for the baby. It is a queer-shaped little creature, and holds out its arms and legs in all directions, like a star-fish. The poor little thing is snorting like a steam-engine when she catches it, and keeps doubling itself up and straightening itself out again, so that she can hardly keep hold.

ALICE
If I don't take this child away with me, they're sure to kill it in a day or two.

She carries it out into the open air.

EXT. WOOD NEAR DUCHESS'S HOUSE - DAY

Alice nurses the baby as she walks.

ALICE
(to the baby)
Don't grunt. That's not at all a proper way of expressing yourself.

The baby grunts again. Alice looks anxiously into its face to see what is the matter. There can be no doubt that it has a very turn-up nose, much more like a snout than a real nose; also its eyes are getting extremely small for a baby.

ALICE
If you're going to turn into a pig, my dear, I'll have nothing more to do with you. Mind now!

The baby grunts again, so violently that she looks down into its face in some alarm. This time there can be no mistake: it is nothing but a pig.

Alice sets it down carefully on the ground. It trots away quietly into the wood.

ALICE
If it had grown up, it would have made a dreadfully ugly child: but it makes rather a handsome pig, I think.

She begins thinking over other children she knows, who might do very well as pigs. Then she is a little startled by seeing the Cheshire Cat sitting on a bough of a tree a few yards off.

The Cat grins when it sees Alice. It looks good-natured, she thinks; still it has very long claws and a great many teeth, so she feels it ought to be treated with respect.

ALICE
Cheshire Puss, would you tell me, please, which way I ought to go from here?

CHESHIRE CAT
That depends a good deal on where you want to get to.

ALICE
I don't much care where —

CHESHIRE CAT
Then it doesn't matter which way you go.

ALICE
— so long as I get somewhere.

CHESHIRE CAT
Oh, you're sure to do that, if you only walk long enough.

Alice feels this cannot be denied, so she tries another question.

ALICE
What sort of people live about here?

CHESHIRE CAT
In that direction lives a Hatter: and in that direction lives a March Hare. Visit either you like: they're both mad.

ALICE
But I don't want to go among mad people.

CHESHIRE CAT
Oh, you can't help that. We're all mad here. I'm mad. You're mad.

ALICE
How do you know I'm mad?

CHESHIRE CAT
You must be, or you wouldn't have come here.

Alice doesn't think that proves it at all; however, she goes on.

ALICE
And how do you know that you're mad?

CHESHIRE CAT
To begin with, a dog's not mad. You grant that?

ALICE
I suppose so.

CHESHIRE CAT
Well, then, you see, a dog growls when it's angry, and wags its tail when it's pleased. Now I growl when I'm pleased, and wag my tail when I'm angry. Therefore I'm mad.

ALICE
I call it purring, not growling.

CHESHIRE CAT
Call it what you like. Do you play croquet with the Queen to-day?

ALICE
I should like it very much, but I haven't been invited yet.

CHESHIRE CAT
You'll see me there.

The Cat vanishes.

Alice is not much surprised; she is getting so used to queer things happening. While she is looking at the place where it had been, it suddenly appears again.

CHESHIRE CAT
By-the-bye, what became of the baby? I'd nearly forgotten to ask.

ALICE
It turned into a pig.

CHESHIRE CAT
I thought it would.

It vanishes again. Alice waits a little, half expecting to see it again, but it does not appear. She walks on in the direction in which the March Hare is said to live.

I have seen hatters before, she thinks: the March Hare will be much the most interesting, and perhaps as this is May it won't be raving mad — at least not so mad as it was in March.

As she says this, she looks up, and there is the Cat again, sitting on a branch of a tree.

CHESHIRE CAT
Did you say pig, or fig?

ALICE
I said pig. And I wish you wouldn't keep appearing and vanishing so suddenly: you make one quite giddy.

CHESHIRE CAT
All right.

This time it vanishes quite slowly, beginning with the end of the tail, and ending with the grin, which remains some time after the rest of it has gone.

ALICE
Well! I've often seen a cat without a grin, but a grin without a cat! It's the most curious thing I ever saw in my life!

She walks on. Soon she comes in sight of the house of the March Hare: she thinks it must be the right house, because the chimneys are shaped like ears and the roof is thatched with fur. It is so large a house that she does not like to go nearer till she has nibbled some more of the left-hand bit of mushroom, and raised herself to about two feet high.

Even then she walks up towards it rather timidly, saying to herself —

ALICE
Suppose it should be raving mad after all! I almost wish I'd gone to see the Hatter instead!

EXT. MARCH HARE'S HOUSE - DAY

A table is set out under a tree in front of the house. The MARCH HARE and the HATTER take tea at it. The DORMOUSE sits between them, fast asleep; the other two use it as a cushion, resting their elbows on it and talking over its head.

ALICE approaches. The three are crowded together at one corner of the large table.

MARCH HARE
No room! No room!

HATTER
No room! No room!

ALICE
There's plenty of room!

She sits down in a large arm-chair at one end of the table.

MARCH HARE
(encouraging)
Have some wine.

Alice looks all round the table: nothing on it but tea.

ALICE
I don't see any wine.

MARCH HARE
There isn't any.

ALICE
(angrily)
Then it wasn't very civil of you to offer it.

MARCH HARE
It wasn't very civil of you to sit down without being invited.

ALICE
I didn't know it was your table. It's laid for a great many more than three.

The Hatter has been looking at Alice with great curiosity.

HATTER
Your hair wants cutting.

ALICE
(with severity)
You should learn not to make personal remarks. It's very rude.

The Hatter opens his eyes very wide.

HATTER
Why is a raven like a writing-desk?

ALICE
(to herself, pleased)
Come, we shall have some fun now! I'm glad they've begun asking riddles.

(aloud)
I believe I can guess that.

MARCH HARE
Do you mean that you think you can find out the answer to it?

ALICE
Exactly so.

MARCH HARE
Then you should say what you mean.

ALICE
I do — at least — at least I mean what I say — that's the same thing, you know.

HATTER
Not the same thing a bit! You might just as well say that "I see what I eat" is the same thing as "I eat what I see"!

MARCH HARE
You might just as well say that "I like what I get" is the same thing as "I get what I like"!

DORMOUSE
(talking in its sleep)
You might just as well say that "I breathe when I sleep" is the same thing as "I sleep when I breathe"!

HATTER
It is the same thing with you.

The conversation drops. They sit silent. Alice thinks hard about ravens and writing-desks.

The Hatter takes a watch from his pocket, looks at it uneasily, shakes it, holds it to his ear.

HATTER
What day of the month is it?

ALICE
The fourth.

HATTER
(sighs)
Two days wrong! I told you butter wouldn't suit the works!

He glares at the March Hare.

MARCH HARE
(meekly)
It was the best butter.

HATTER
Yes, but some crumbs must have got in as well. You shouldn't have put it in with the bread-knife.

The March Hare takes the watch, looks at it gloomily, dips it into his cup of tea, looks again.

MARCH HARE
It was the best butter, you know.

Alice looks over his shoulder.

ALICE
What a funny watch! It tells the day of the month, and doesn't tell what o'clock it is!

HATTER
Why should it? Does your watch tell you what year it is?

ALICE
Of course not. But that's because it stays the same year for such a long time together.

HATTER
Which is just the case with mine.

ALICE
(politely)
I don't quite understand you.

HATTER
The Dormouse is asleep again.

He pours a little hot tea upon its nose. The Dormouse shakes its head impatiently, eyes still shut.

DORMOUSE
Of course, of course; just what I was going to remark myself.

HATTER
Have you guessed the riddle yet?

ALICE
No, I give it up. What's the answer?

HATTER
I haven't the slightest idea.

MARCH HARE
Nor I.

Alice sighs wearily.

ALICE
I think you might do something better with the time than waste it in asking riddles that have no answers.

HATTER
If you knew Time as well as I do, you wouldn't talk about wasting it. It's him.

ALICE
I don't know what you mean.

HATTER
(tossing his head)
Of course you don't! I dare say you never even spoke to Time!

ALICE
Perhaps not. But I know I have to beat time when I learn music.

HATTER
Ah! that accounts for it. He won't stand beating. Now, if you only kept on good terms with him, he'd do almost anything you liked with the clock. For instance, suppose it were nine o'clock in the morning, just time to begin lessons: you'd only have to whisper a hint to Time, and round goes the clock in a twinkling! Half-past one, time for dinner!

MARCH HARE
(whispers to itself)
I only wish it was.

ALICE
That would be grand, certainly. But then — I shouldn't be hungry for it, you know.

HATTER
Not at first, perhaps. But you could keep it to half-past one as long as you liked.

ALICE
Is that the way you manage?

The Hatter shakes his head mournfully.

HATTER
Not I! We quarrelled last March — just before he went mad, you know —

(points his tea spoon at the March Hare)

— it was at the great concert given by the Queen of Hearts, and I had to sing

"Twinkle, twinkle, little bat!
How I wonder what you're at!"

You know the song, perhaps?

ALICE
I've heard something like it.

HATTER
It goes on, you know, in this way: —

"Up above the world you fly,
Like a tea-tray in the sky.
Twinkle, twinkle —"

The Dormouse shakes itself and sings in its sleep.

DORMOUSE
Twinkle, twinkle, twinkle, twinkle —

They pinch it to make it stop.

HATTER
Well, I'd hardly finished the first verse, when the Queen jumped up and bawled out, "He's murdering the time! Off with his head!"

ALICE
How dreadfully savage!

HATTER
(mournful)
And ever since that, he won't do a thing I ask! It's always six o'clock now.

ALICE
Is that the reason so many tea-things are put out here?

HATTER
(sighs)
Yes, that's it. It's always tea-time, and we've no time to wash the things between whiles.

ALICE
Then you keep moving round, I suppose?

HATTER
Exactly so. As the things get used up.

ALICE
But what happens when you come to the beginning again?

MARCH HARE
(yawning)
Suppose we change the subject. I'm getting tired of this. I vote the young lady tells us a story.

ALICE
(alarmed)
I'm afraid I don't know one.

MARCH HARE
Then the Dormouse shall!

HATTER
Wake up, Dormouse!

They pinch it on both sides at once. The Dormouse slowly opens its eyes.

DORMOUSE
(hoarse, feeble)
I wasn't asleep. I heard every word you fellows were saying.

MARCH HARE
Tell us a story!

ALICE
Yes, please do!

HATTER
And be quick about it, or you'll be asleep again before it's done.

DORMOUSE
(in a great hurry)
Once upon a time there were three little sisters, and their names were Elsie, Lacie, and Tillie; and they lived at the bottom of a well —

ALICE
What did they live on?

DORMOUSE
(after a moment)
They lived on treacle.

ALICE
They couldn't have done that, you know. They'd have been ill.

DORMOUSE
So they were. Very ill.

ALICE
But why did they live at the bottom of a well?

MARCH HARE
(earnestly)
Take some more tea.

ALICE
(offended)
I've had nothing yet, so I can't take more.

HATTER
You mean you can't take less. It's very easy to take more than nothing.

ALICE
Nobody asked your opinion.

HATTER
(triumphantly)
Who's making personal remarks now?

Alice helps herself to tea and bread-and-butter, then turns back to the Dormouse.

ALICE
Why did they live at the bottom of a well?

DORMOUSE
(after thinking)
It was a treacle-well.

ALICE
(angrily)
There's no such thing!

HATTER
Sh! sh!

MARCH HARE
Sh! sh!

DORMOUSE
(sulkily)
If you can't be civil, you'd better finish the story for yourself.

ALICE
(humbly)
No, please go on! I won't interrupt again. I dare say there may be one.

DORMOUSE
One, indeed!

(consents to go on)
And so these three little sisters — they were learning to draw, you know —

ALICE
What did they draw?

DORMOUSE
Treacle.

HATTER
I want a clean cup. Let's all move one place on.

He moves on. The Dormouse follows him. The March Hare moves into the Dormouse's place. Alice rather unwillingly takes the place of the March Hare. The March Hare has just upset the milk-jug into his plate; Alice is worse off than before.

ALICE
(cautiously)
But I don't understand. Where did they draw the treacle from?

HATTER
You can draw water out of a water-well, so I should think you could draw treacle out of a treacle-well — eh, stupid?

ALICE
(to the Dormouse)
But they were in the well.

DORMOUSE
Of course they were — well in.

Alice is too confused to interrupt. The Dormouse yawns, rubs its eyes, growing sleepy.

DORMOUSE
They were learning to draw, and they drew all manner of things — everything that begins with an M —

ALICE
Why with an M?

MARCH HARE
Why not?

Alice is silent. The Dormouse closes its eyes; the Hatter pinches it. It wakes with a little shriek.

DORMOUSE
— that begins with an M, such as mouse-traps, and the moon, and memory, and muchness — you know you say things are "much of a muchness" — did you ever see such a thing as a drawing of a muchness?

ALICE
(confused)
Really, now you ask me, I don't think —

HATTER
Then you shouldn't talk.

Alice gets up in great disgust and walks off. The Dormouse falls asleep instantly. Neither of the others takes the least notice. She looks back once or twice; the last time she sees them, they are trying to put the Dormouse into the teapot.

EXT. WOOD NEAR MARCH HARE'S HOUSE - DAY

Alice picks her way through the wood.

ALICE
At any rate I'll never go there again! It's the stupidest tea-party I ever was at in all my life!

She notices that one of the trees has a door leading right into it.

ALICE
(to herself)
That's very curious! But everything's curious today. I think I may as well go in at once.

She goes in.

INT. LONG LOW HALL - DAY

Once more she finds herself in the long hall, close to the little glass table.

ALICE
Now, I'll manage better this time.

She takes the little golden key and unlocks the door that leads into the garden. She nibbles at the mushroom from her pocket till she is about a foot high, then walks down the little passage.

EXT. QUEEN'S GARDEN - DAY

Alice finds herself at last in the beautiful garden, among bright flower-beds and cool fountains.

A large rose-tree stands near the entrance: the roses on it are white, but three gardeners — TWO, FIVE, and SEVEN — are busily painting them red. Alice goes nearer.

TWO
Look out now, Five! Don't go splashing paint over me like that!

FIVE
(sulky)
I couldn't help it. Seven jogged my elbow.

SEVEN
That's right, Five! Always lay the blame on others!

FIVE
You'd better not talk! I heard the Queen say only yesterday you deserved to be beheaded!

TWO
What for?

SEVEN
That's none of your business, Two!

FIVE
Yes, it is his business! And I'll tell him — it was for bringing the cook tulip-roots instead of onions.

Seven flings down his brush.

SEVEN
Well, of all the unjust things —

His eye falls upon Alice. He checks himself. The others look round; all three bow low.

ALICE
(timidly)
Would you tell me why you are painting those roses?

Five and Seven look at Two.

TWO
(low voice)
Why the fact is, you see, Miss, this here ought to have been a red rose-tree, and we put a white one in by mistake; and if the Queen was to find it out, we should all have our heads cut off, you know. So you see, Miss, we're doing our best, afore she comes, to —

FIVE
(looking across the garden)
The Queen! The Queen!

The three gardeners throw themselves flat upon their faces. A sound of many footsteps. Alice looks round, eager to see the Queen.

First come ten SOLDIERS carrying clubs — oblong and flat, hands and feet at the corners, shaped like the gardeners. Next ten COURTIERS ornamented with diamonds, walking two and two. Then ten royal children ornamented with hearts, jumping merrily hand in hand in couples. Then guests, mostly Kings and Queens; among them the WHITE RABBIT, talking in a hurried nervous manner, smiling at everything, going by without noticing Alice. Then the KNAVE OF HEARTS, carrying the King's crown on a crimson velvet cushion. Last of all: the KING OF HEARTS and the QUEEN OF HEARTS.

Alice stands still where she is and waits. When the procession comes opposite her, they all stop and look at her.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(severely, to the Knave)
Who is this?

The Knave only bows and smiles.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Idiot!

(to Alice)
What's your name, child?

ALICE
(very politely)
My name is Alice, so please your Majesty.

(to herself)
Why, they're only a pack of cards, after all. I needn't be afraid of them!

QUEEN OF HEARTS
And who are these?

She points to the three gardeners lying round the rose-tree.

ALICE
(surprised at her own courage)
How should I know? It's no business of mine.

The Queen turns crimson with fury, glares like a wild beast.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Off with her head! Off —

ALICE
(loudly and decidedly)
Nonsense!

The Queen is silent. The King lays his hand upon her arm.

KING OF HEARTS
(timidly)
Consider, my dear: she is only a child!

The Queen turns angrily away from him.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(to the Knave)
Turn them over!

The Knave does so, very carefully, with one foot.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(shrill, loud)
Get up!

The three gardeners jump up and begin bowing to the King, the Queen, the royal children, and everybody else.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Leave off that! You make me giddy.

(turning to the rose-tree)
What have you been doing here?

TWO
(humble, on one knee)
May it please your Majesty, we were trying —

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(examining the roses)
I see! Off with their heads!

The procession moves on. Three soldiers remain behind to execute the gardeners, who run to Alice for protection.

ALICE
You shan't be beheaded!

She puts them into a large flower-pot that stands near. The three soldiers wander about looking for them, then quietly march off after the others.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(shouting)
Are their heads off?

SOLDIERS
Their heads are gone, if it please your Majesty!

QUEEN OF HEARTS
That's right! Can you play croquet?

The soldiers look at Alice.

ALICE
(shouting)
Yes!

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Come on, then!

Alice joins the procession.

EXT. CROQUET-GROUND - DAY

Alice walks beside the White Rabbit, who peeps anxiously into her face.

WHITE RABBIT
(timid)
It's — it's a very fine day!

ALICE
Very. — Where's the Duchess?

WHITE RABBIT
Hush! Hush!

He looks anxiously over his shoulder, raises himself upon tiptoe, puts his mouth close to her ear.

WHITE RABBIT
(whispers)
She's under sentence of execution.

ALICE
What for?

WHITE RABBIT
Did you say "What a pity!"?

ALICE
No, I didn't. I don't think it's at all a pity. I said "What for?"

WHITE RABBIT
She boxed the Queen's ears —

Alice gives a little scream of laughter.

WHITE RABBIT
(frightened whisper)
Oh, hush! The Queen will hear you! You see, she came rather late, and the Queen said —

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(voice of thunder)
Get to your places!

People run about in all directions, tumbling up against each other; they settle down. The game begins.

The croquet-ground is all ridges and furrows. The balls are live hedgehogs, the mallets live flamingoes, and the soldiers double themselves up and stand on their hands and feet to make the arches.

Alice tucks a flamingo's body under her arm, legs hanging down. Just as she gets its neck straightened to strike the hedgehog, it twists round and looks up in her face with a puzzled expression; she bursts out laughing. When she gets its head down again, the hedgehog has unrolled and is crawling away. Ridges and furrows block every aim; the doubled-up soldiers keep getting up and walking off.

All the players play at once, without waiting for turns, quarrelling all the while, and fighting for the hedgehogs. The Queen goes about, stamping about, and shouting "Off with his head!" or "Off with her head!" about once in a minute.

Alice begins to feel very uneasy. She has never been in a court of justice before, but she has read about them, and she is quite pleased to find that she knows the name of nearly everything there.

She looks up — and there is the Cheshire Cat in the air. It is grinning from ear to ear.

ALICE
How are you getting on?

CHESHIRE CAT
(as well as it can for grinning)
I said you would see me here.

The Cat's head only appears; Alice waits to see if it will appear any more, but it does not.

ALICE
I don't think they play at all fairly, and they all quarrel so dreadfully one can't hear oneself speak — and they don't seem to have any rules in particular; at least, if there are, nobody attends to them — and you've no idea how confusing it is all the things being alive; for instance, there's the arch I've got to go through next walking about at the other end of the ground — and I should have croqueted the Queen's hedgehog just now, only it ran away when it saw mine coming!

CHESHIRE CAT
How do you like the Queen?

ALICE
Not at all. She's so extremely —

Just then she notices that the Queen is close behind her, listening. She goes on —

ALICE
— likely to win, that it's hardly worth while finishing the game.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(in a low, deep voice)
Who are you talking to?

ALICE
(very politely)
It's a friend of mine — a Cheshire Cat. Allow me to introduce it.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
I don't like the look of it at all. However, it may kiss my hand if it likes.

CHESHIRE CAT
I'd rather not.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Don't be impertinent, and don't look at me like that!

She turns to the King.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Off with his head!

KING OF HEARTS
(timidly)
I don't see it at all. Where did you say it was?

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(pointing)
It's over there. I don't like the look of it at all. However, it may kiss my hand, if it likes.

The King and executioner argue whether a head can be beheaded without a body. The Cat's head begins to fade away. By the time they have settled anything, the head is entirely gone.

The Queen stamps off, shouting "Off with his head!" at anyone who happens to be in her way.

Alice thinks she had better go back and see how the game is going on. She hears the Queen's voice in the distance, screaming with passion. She has already heard her sentence three of the players to be executed for having missed their turns.

Alice leaves the croquet-ground. She finds the Duchess's arm slipped through hers, and the Duchess smiling in a pleasant way.

DUCHESS
You can't think how glad I am to see you again, you dear old thing!

Alice is very glad to find her in such a pleasant temper, and thinks to herself that perhaps it was only the pepper that had made her so savage when they met in the kitchen.

DUCHESS
(tucking her arm tighter)
You're thinking about something, my dear, and that makes you forget to talk. I can't tell you just now what the moral of that is, but I shall remember it in a bit.

ALICE
Perhaps it hasn't one.

DUCHESS
Tut, tut, child! Everything's got a moral, if only you can find it.

She squeezes herself up closer to Alice's side as she speaks.

Alice does not much like keeping so close to her: first, because the Duchess is very ugly; and secondly, because she is exactly the right height to rest her chin upon Alice's shoulder, and it is an uncomfortably sharp chin.

DUCHESS
The game's going on rather better now.

A pause. The Duchess begins again.

DUCHESS
'Tis so, and the moral of that is — "Oh, 'tis love, 'tis love, that makes the world go round!"

ALICE
Somebody said that the world goes round much faster than usual when one is spinning round.

DUCHESS
(digging her sharp little chin into Alice's shoulder)
Exactly so. And the moral of that is — "Take care of the sense, and the sounds will take care of themselves."

ALICE
How fond she is of finding morals in things!

DUCHESS
I dare say you're wondering why I don't put my arm round your waist. The reason is, that I'm doubtful about the temper of your flamingo. Shall I try the experiment?

ALICE
He might bite.

DUCHESS
Very true. Flamingoes and mustard both bite. And the moral of that is — "Birds of a feather flock together."

ALICE
Only mustard isn't a bird.

DUCHESS
Right, as usual. What a clear way you have of putting things!

ALICE
It's a mineral, I think.

DUCHESS
Of course it is. There's a large mustard-mine near here. And the moral of that is — "The more there is of mine, the less there is of yours."

ALICE
Oh, I know! It's a vegetable. It doesn't look like one, but it is.

DUCHESS
I quite agree with you. And the moral of that is — "Be what you would seem to be" — or if you'd like it put more simply — "Never imagine yourself not to be otherwise than what it might appear to others that what you were or might have been was not otherwise than what you had been would have appeared to them to be otherwise."

ALICE
I think I should understand that better if I had it written down: but I can't quite follow it as you say it.

DUCHESS
That's nothing to what I could say if I chose.

ALICE
Pray don't trouble yourself to say it any longer than that.

DUCHESS
Oh, don't talk about trouble! I make you a present of everything I've said as yet.

A voice in the distance —

QUEEN OF HEARTS (O.S.)
A large rose-tree stood near the entrance of the garden: the roses growing on it were white, but there were three gardeners at it, busily painting them red —

No — the Queen's actual shout:

QUEEN OF HEARTS (O.S.)
Get to your places!

The Duchess flees. The Queen appears, and Alice is invited — ordered — to continue the game. But Alice is tired of it. The Queen says —

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Have you seen the Mock Turtle yet?

ALICE
No. I don't even know what a Mock Turtle is.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
It's the thing Mock Turtle Soup is made from.

ALICE
I never saw one, or heard of one.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Come on, then, and he shall tell you his history.

As they walk off together, Alice hears the King say in a low voice to the company generally —

KING OF HEARTS
You are all pardoned.

The soldiers and guests look immensely relieved.

EXT. EDGE OF THE CROQUET-GROUND - DAY

The Queen leads Alice to the GRYPHON, who lies fast asleep in the sun.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(to the Gryphon)
Up, lazy thing, and take this young lady to see the Mock Turtle, and to hear his history. I must go back and see after some executions I have ordered.

She walks off, leaving Alice alone with the Gryphon. Alice does not quite like the look of the creature, but on the whole she thinks it would be quite as safe to stay with it as to go after that savage Queen: so she waits.

The Gryphon sits up and rubs its eyes. It watches the Queen till she is out of sight, then chuckles.

GRYPHON
What fun!

ALICE
What is the fun?

GRYPHON
Why, she. It's all her fancy, that: they never executes nobody, you know. Come on!

They walk on together. Alice hears the Mock Turtle's heavy sobs in the distance long before they come in sight of him.

EXT. MOCK TURTLE'S ROCK - DAY

The MOCK TURTLE sits sad and lonely on a little ledge of rock, sighing as if his heart would break. He looks at them with large eyes full of tears, but says nothing.

GRYPHON
This here young lady, she wants for to know your history, she do.

MOCK TURTLE
I'll tell it her. Sit down, both of you, and don't speak a word till I've finished.

So they sit down, and nobody speaks for some minutes. Alice thinks to herself, I don't see how he can ever finish, if he doesn't begin.

But she waits patiently.

MOCK TURTLE
Once, I was a real Turtle.

He sighs deeply, drawing the back of one flapper across his eyes. He tries to speak; sobs choke his voice.

GRYPHON
Same as if he had a bone in his throat.

The Gryphon shakes him and punches him in the back. At last the Mock Turtle recovers, tears running down his cheeks.

MOCK TURTLE
When we were little, we went to school in the sea. The master was an old Turtle — we used to call him Tortoise —

ALICE
Why did you call him Tortoise, if he wasn't one?

MOCK TURTLE
We called him Tortoise because he taught us. Really you are very dull!

GRYPHON
You ought to be ashamed of yourself for asking such a simple question. Drive on, old fellow! Don't be all day about it!

MOCK TURTLE
Yes, we went to school in the sea, though you mayn't believe it —

ALICE
I never said I didn't!

MOCK TURTLE
You did. We had the best of educations — in fact, we went to school every day —

ALICE
I've been to a day-school, too. You needn't be so proud as all that.

MOCK TURTLE
With extras?

ALICE
Yes, we learned French and music.

MOCK TURTLE
And washing?

ALICE
Certainly not!

MOCK TURTLE
Ah! then yours wasn't a really good school. Now at ours they had at the end of the bill, "French, music, and washing — extra."

ALICE
You couldn't have wanted it much, living at the bottom of the sea.

MOCK TURTLE
I couldn't afford to learn it. I only took the regular course.

ALICE
What was that?

MOCK TURTLE
Reeling and Writhing, of course, to begin with, and then the different branches of Arithmetic — Ambition, Distraction, Uglification, and Derision.

ALICE
I never heard of "Uglification." What is it?

The Gryphon lifts up both its paws in surprise.

GRYPHON
Never heard of uglifying! You know what to beautify is, I suppose?

ALICE
Yes. It means — to — make — anything — prettier.

GRYPHON
Well, then, if you don't know what to uglify is, you are a simpleton.

Alice does not feel encouraged to ask any more questions about it, so she turns to the Mock Turtle.

ALICE
What else had you to learn?

MOCK TURTLE
Well, there was Mystery, ancient and modern, with Seaography: then Drawling — the Drawling-master was an old conger-eel, that used to come once a week: he taught us Drawling, Stretching, and Fainting in Coils.

ALICE
What was that like?

MOCK TURTLE
Well, I can't show it you myself. I'm too stiff. And the Gryphon never learnt it.

GRYPHON
Hadn't time. I went to the Classical master, though. He was an old crab, he was.

MOCK TURTLE
I never went to him. He taught Laughing and Grief, they used to say.

GRYPHON
So he did, so he did.

They both bury their faces in their paws.

ALICE
And how many hours a day did you do lessons?

MOCK TURTLE
Ten hours the first day, nine the next, and so on.

ALICE
What a curious plan!

GRYPHON
That's the reason they're called lessons — because they lessen from day to day.

This is quite a new idea to Alice, and she thinks it over a little before she makes her next remark.

ALICE
Then the eleventh day must have been a holiday?

MOCK TURTLE
Of course it was.

ALICE
And how did you manage on the twelfth?

GRYPHON
That's enough about lessons. Tell her something about the games now.

The Mock Turtle sighs deeply and draws the back of one flapper across his eyes. He tries to speak; sobs choke his voice.

GRYPHON
Same as if he had a bone in his throat.

The Gryphon shakes him and punches him in the back. At last the Mock Turtle recovers.

MOCK TURTLE
You may not have lived much under the sea —

ALICE
I haven't.

MOCK TURTLE
— and perhaps you were never even introduced to a lobster —

Alice begins to say something, checks herself.

ALICE
No, never.

MOCK TURTLE
— so you can have no idea what a delightful thing a Lobster Quadrille is!

ALICE
No, indeed. What sort of a dance is it?

GRYPHON
Why, you first form into a line along the sea-shore —

MOCK TURTLE
Two lines! Seals, turtles, salmon, and so on; then, when you've cleared all the jelly-fish out of the way —

GRYPHON
THAT generally takes some time.

MOCK TURTLE
— you advance twice —

GRYPHON
Each with a lobster as a partner!

MOCK TURTLE
Of course: advance twice, set to partners —

GRYPHON
— change lobsters, and retire in same order.

MOCK TURTLE
Then, you know, you throw the —

GRYPHON
(with a bound into the air)
The lobsters!

MOCK TURTLE
— as far out to sea as you can —

GRYPHON
(screaming)
Swim after them!

MOCK TURTLE
(capering wildly)
Turn a somersault in the sea!

GRYPHON
(yelling)
Change lobsters again!

MOCK TURTLE
(suddenly dropping his voice)
Back to land again, and that's all the first figure.

The two creatures, who have been jumping about like mad things, sit down again very sadly and quietly and look at Alice.

ALICE
(timidly)
It must be a very pretty dance.

MOCK TURTLE
Would you like to see a little of it?

ALICE
Very much indeed.

MOCK TURTLE
Come, let's try the first figure! We can do without lobsters, you know. Which shall sing?

GRYPHON
Oh, YOU sing. I've forgotten the words.

They begin solemnly dancing round and round Alice, every now and then treading on her toes, waving their forepaws to mark the time. The Mock Turtle sings very slowly and sadly.

MOCK TURTLE
(singing)
"Will you walk a little faster?" said a whiting to a snail.
"There's a porpoise close behind us, and he's treading on my tail.

See how eagerly the lobsters and the turtles all advance!
They are waiting on the shingle — will you come and join the dance?

Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, will you join the dance?
Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, won't you join the dance?

"You can really have no notion how delightful it will be
When they take us up and throw us, with the lobsters, out to sea!"
But the snail replied "Too far, too far!" and gave a look askance —
Said he thanked the whiting kindly, but he would not join the dance.

Would not, could not, would not, could not, would not join the dance.
Would not, could not, would not, could not, could not join the dance.

"What matters it how far we go?" his scaly friend replied.
"There is another shore, you know, upon the other side.
The further off from England the nearer is to France —
Then turn not pale, beloved snail, but come and join the dance.

Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, will you join the dance?
Will you, won't you, will you, won't you, won't you join the dance?"

ALICE
(glad it is over)
Thank you, it's a very interesting dance to watch, and I do so like that curious song about the whiting!

MOCK TURTLE
Oh, as to the whiting, they — you've seen them, of course?

ALICE
Yes, I've often seen them at dinn —

She checks herself hastily.

MOCK TURTLE
I don't know where Dinn may be, but if you've seen them so often, of course you know what they're like.

ALICE
(thoughtfully)
I believe so. They have their tails in their mouths — and they're all over crumbs.

MOCK TURTLE
You're wrong about the crumbs: crumbs would all wash off in the sea. But they HAVE their tails in their mouths; and the reason is —

He yawns and shuts his eyes.

MOCK TURTLE
Tell her about the reason and all that.

GRYPHON
The reason is that they WOULD go with the lobsters to the dance. So they got thrown out to sea. So they had to fall a long way. So they got their tails fast in their mouths. So they couldn't get them out again. That's all.

ALICE
Thank you, it's very interesting. I never knew so much about a whiting before.

GRYPHON
I can tell you more than that, if you like. Do you know why it's called a whiting?

ALICE
I never thought about it. Why?

GRYPHON
(solemnly)
IT DOES THE BOOTS AND SHOES.

ALICE
(wondering)
Does the boots and shoes!

GRYPHON
Why, what are YOUR shoes done with? I mean, what makes them so shiny?

Alice looks down at her shoes.

ALICE
They're done with blacking, I believe.

GRYPHON
(in a deep voice)
Boots and shoes under the sea are done with a whiting. Now you know.

ALICE
And what are they made of?

GRYPHON
(impatiently)
Soles and eels, of course: any shrimp could have told you that.

ALICE
If I'd been the whiting, I'd have said to the porpoise, "Keep back, please: we don't want YOU with us!"

MOCK TURTLE
They were obliged to have him with them: no wise fish would go anywhere without a porpoise.

ALICE
(surprised)
Wouldn't it really?

MOCK TURTLE
Of course not: why, if a fish came to ME, and told me he was going a journey, I should say "With what porpoise?"

ALICE
Don't you mean "purpose"?

MOCK TURTLE
(offended)
I mean what I say.

GRYPHON
Come, let's hear some of YOUR adventures.

ALICE
(a little timidly)
I could tell you my adventures — beginning from this morning: but it's no use going back to yesterday, because I was a different person then.

MOCK TURTLE
Explain all that.

GRYPHON
(impatient)
No, no! The adventures first: explanations take such a dreadful time.

Alice begins telling them her adventures from the time she first saw the White Rabbit. The two creatures get close, one on each side, eyes and mouths VERY wide. She gains courage as she goes on. They are quiet till she reaches the part about repeating "You Are Old, Father William" to the Caterpillar, and the words all coming different.

MOCK TURTLE
(drawing a long breath)
That's very curious.

GRYPHON
It's all about as curious as it can be.

MOCK TURTLE
(thoughtfully)
It all came different! I should like to hear her try and repeat something now. Tell her to begin.

He looks at the Gryphon as if it had authority over Alice.

GRYPHON
Stand up and repeat "'Tis the Voice of the Sluggard."

Alice gets up. Her head is full of the Lobster Quadrille; the words come very queer.

ALICE
'Tis the voice of the Lobster; I heard him declare,
"You have baked me too brown, I must sugar my hair."
As a duck with its eyelids, so he with his nose
Trims his belt and his buttons, and turns out his toes.

When the sands are all dry, he is gay as a lark,
And will talk in contemptuous tones of the Shark,
But, when the tide rises and sharks are around,
His voice has a timid and tremulous sound.

GRYPHON
That's different from what I used to say when I was a child.

MOCK TURTLE
Well, I never heard it before, but it sounds uncommon nonsense.

Alice sits down with her face in her hands.

MOCK TURTLE
I should like to have it explained.

GRYPHON
(hastily)
She can't explain it. Go on with the next verse.

MOCK TURTLE
But about his toes? How COULD he turn them out with his nose, you know?

ALICE
It's the first position in dancing.

GRYPHON
(impatiently)
Go on with the next verse: it begins "I passed by his garden."

Alice goes on in a trembling voice.

ALICE
I passed by his garden, and marked, with one eye,
How the Owl and the Panther were sharing a pie —

The Panther took pie-crust, and gravy, and meat,
While the Owl had the dish as its share of the treat.
When the pie was all finished, the Owl, as a boon,
Was kindly permitted to pocket the spoon:
While the Panther received knife and fork with a growl,
And concluded the banquet —

MOCK TURTLE
(interrupting)
What IS the use of repeating all that stuff, if you don't explain it as you go on? It's by far the most confusing thing I ever heard!

GRYPHON
Yes, I think you'd better leave off.

Alice is only too glad to do so.

GRYPHON
Shall we try another figure of the Lobster Quadrille? Or would you like the Mock Turtle to sing you a song?

ALICE
(eagerly)
Oh, a song, please, if the Mock Turtle would be so kind.

GRYPHON
(rather offended)
Hm! No accounting for tastes! Sing her "Turtle Soup," will you, old fellow?

The Mock Turtle sighs deeply and begins, voice sometimes choked with sobs.

MOCK TURTLE
(singing)
Beautiful Soup, so rich and green,
Waiting in a hot tureen!
Who for such dainties would not stoop?
Soup of the evening, beautiful Soup!
Soup of the evening, beautiful Soup!
Beau — ootiful Soo — oop!
Beau — ootiful Soo — oop!
Soo — oop of the e — e — evening,
Beautiful, beautiful Soup!

Beautiful Soup! Who cares for fish,
Game, or any other dish?
Who would not give all else for two
Pennyworth only of beautiful Soup?
Pennyworth only of beautiful Soup?
Beau — ootiful Soo — oop!
Beau — ootiful Soo — oop!
Soo — oop of the e — e — evening,
Beautiful, beauti — FUL SOUP!

GRYPHON
Chorus again!

The Mock Turtle has just begun to repeat it when a cry is heard in the distance.

VOICE (O.S.)
The trial's beginning!

GRYPHON
Come on!

The Gryphon takes Alice by the hand and hurries off, without waiting for the end of the song.

ALICE
(panting as she runs)
What trial is it?

GRYPHON
Come on!

They run faster. More and more faintly on the breeze come the melancholy words.

MOCK TURTLE (O.S.)
Soo — oop of the e — e — evening,
Beautiful, beautiful Soup!

EXT. COURT OF HEARTS - DAY

The KING OF HEARTS and QUEEN OF HEARTS sit on their throne. A great crowd of little birds and beasts and the whole pack of cards assembles about them. The KNAVE OF HEARTS stands before them in chains, a SOLDIER on each side. Near the King stands the WHITE RABBIT, trumpet in one hand, scroll of parchment in the other. In the middle of the court: a table with a large dish of tarts.

Alice and the Gryphon arrive. Alice eyes the tarts hungrily.

Alice looks about, pleased to know the names of things. The King wears his crown over a great wig and does not look comfortable. Twelve jurors — animals and birds mixed — write busily on slates in the jury-box. Among them: BILL THE LIZARD.

ALICE
(whispering to the Gryphon)
What are they doing? They can't have anything to put down yet, before the trial's begun.

GRYPHON
(whispering)
They're putting down their names, for fear they should forget them before the end of the trial.

ALICE
(loud, indignant)
Stupid things!

WHITE RABBIT
Silence in the court!

The King puts on his spectacles and looks anxiously round. The jurors write down "stupid things!" on their slates. One asks his neighbour how to spell "stupid."

One juror's pencil squeaks. Alice cannot stand it. She goes round behind BILL THE LIZARD and takes the pencil away so quickly he cannot make out what has become of it. After hunting about, he is obliged to write with one finger for the rest of the day — which leaves no mark.

KING OF HEARTS
Herald, read the accusation!

The White Rabbit blows three blasts on the trumpet, unrolls the parchment, and reads.

WHITE RABBIT
The Queen of Hearts, she made some tarts,
All on a summer day:
The Knave of Hearts, he stole those tarts,
And took them quite away!

KING OF HEARTS
Consider your verdict.

WHITE RABBIT
(hastily)
Not yet, not yet! There's a great deal to come before that!

KING OF HEARTS
Call the first witness.

The White Rabbit blows three blasts.

WHITE RABBIT
First witness!

The HATTER comes in with a teacup in one hand and a piece of bread-and-butter in the other. The MARCH HARE follows, arm-in-arm with the DORMOUSE.

HATTER
I beg pardon, your Majesty, for bringing these in: but I hadn't quite finished my tea when I was sent for.

KING OF HEARTS
You ought to have finished. When did you begin?

The Hatter looks at the March Hare.

HATTER
Fourteenth of March, I think it was.

MARCH HARE
Fifteenth.

DORMOUSE
Sixteenth.

KING OF HEARTS
Write that down.

The jury eagerly writes all three dates, adds them up, and reduces the answer to shillings and pence.

KING OF HEARTS
Take off your hat.

HATTER
It isn't mine.

KING OF HEARTS
(turning to the jury)
Stolen!

The jury makes a memorandum.

HATTER
I keep them to sell: I've none of my own. I'm a hatter.

The Queen puts on her spectacles and stares at the Hatter. He turns pale and fidgets.

KING OF HEARTS
Give your evidence, and don't be nervous, or I'll have you executed on the spot.

The Hatter shifts from one foot to the other, looking uneasily at the Queen. In his confusion he bites a large piece out of his teacup instead of the bread-and-butter.

Alice feels a curious sensation: she is beginning to grow larger again. She decides to remain as long as there is room.

DORMOUSE
(sitting next to her)
I wish you wouldn't squeeze so. I can hardly breathe.

ALICE
(meekly)
I can't help it: I'm growing.

DORMOUSE
You've no right to grow here.

ALICE
(more boldly)
Don't talk nonsense: you know you're growing too.

DORMOUSE
Yes, but I grow at a reasonable pace: not in that ridiculous fashion.

He gets up sulkily and crosses to the other side of the court.

The Queen has never left off staring at the Hatter. As the Dormouse crosses, she speaks to an officer.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Bring me the list of the singers in the last concert!

The wretched Hatter trembles so that he shakes both his shoes off.

KING OF HEARTS
(angrily)
Give your evidence, or I'll have you executed, whether you're nervous or not.

HATTER
(trembling)
I'm a poor man, your Majesty — and I hadn't begun my tea — not above a week or so — and what with the bread-and-butter getting so thin — and the twinkling of the tea —

KING OF HEARTS
The twinkling of the what?

HATTER
It began with the tea.

KING OF HEARTS
(sharply)
Of course twinkling begins with a T! Do you take me for a dunce? Go on!

HATTER
I'm a poor man, and most things twinkled after that — only the March Hare said —

MARCH HARE
(in a great hurry)
I didn't!

HATTER
You did!

MARCH HARE
I deny it!

KING OF HEARTS
He denies it: leave out that part.

HATTER
Well, at any rate, the Dormouse said —

He looks anxiously round. The Dormouse is fast asleep and denies nothing.

HATTER
After that, I cut some more bread-and-butter —

A JUROR
But what did the Dormouse say?

HATTER
That I can't remember.

KING OF HEARTS
You MUST remember, or I'll have you executed.

The miserable Hatter drops his teacup and bread-and-butter and goes down on one knee.

HATTER
I'm a poor man, your Majesty.

KING OF HEARTS
You're a very poor speaker.

One of the GUINEA-PIGS cheers and is immediately suppressed by officers: they slip him head first into a large canvas bag, tie it up, and sit upon it.

Alice watches with interest.

KING OF HEARTS
If that's all you know about it, you may stand down.

HATTER
I can't go no lower: I'm on the floor, as it is.

KING OF HEARTS
Then you may SIT down.

The other guinea-pig cheers and is suppressed the same way.

HATTER
(anxious look at the Queen)
I'd rather finish my tea.

KING OF HEARTS
You may go.

The Hatter hurriedly leaves the court, without even waiting to put his shoes on.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(to one of the officers)
— and just take his head off outside.

The officer looks anxiously at the Hatter, who is out of sight before the officer can get to the door.

KING OF HEARTS
Call the next witness!

The next witness is the Duchess's cook. She carries the pepper-box in her hand. Alice guesses who it is, even before she gets into the court, by the way the people near the door begin sneezing.

KING OF HEARTS
Give your evidence.

COOK
Shan't.

The King looks anxiously at the White Rabbit, who says in a low voice —

WHITE RABBIT
Your Majesty must cross-examine this witness.

KING OF HEARTS
Well, if I must, I must.

(in a deep voice)
What are tarts made of?

COOK
Pepper, mostly.

DORMOUSE
(waking with a little shriek)
Treacle.

A general confusion. The Queen has the Dormouse turned out of court. The whole jury has to write down all the dates on their slates, and then add them up.

KING OF HEARTS
Never mind!

COOK
(to Alice, as she leaves)
I won't stand this any longer!

As she leaves, the Dormouse is being carried out, and Alice hears him say —

DORMOUSE (O.S.)
I wish you wouldn't squeeze so.

KING OF HEARTS
Call the next witness!

Alice watches the White Rabbit as he fumbles over the list, feeling very curious to see what the next witness will be like.

WHITE RABBIT
(reading out at the top of his shrill little voice)
Alice!

ALICE
Here!

She jumps up in such a hurry that she tips over the jury-box with the edge of her skirt, upsetting all the jurymen on to the heads of the crowd below. She hastily puts them back — some the wrong way up.

ALICE
Oh, I beg your pardon!

KING OF HEARTS
The trial cannot proceed until all the jurymen are back in their proper places — all.

Alice puts them right as quickly as she can. Bill the Lizard is in the mouth of the bag, and she has to tip him out and put him back with the others.

KING OF HEARTS
What do you know about this business?

ALICE
Nothing.

KING OF HEARTS
Nothing whatever?

ALICE
Nothing whatever.

KING OF HEARTS
That's very important.

WHITE RABBIT
Unimportant, your Majesty means, of course.

KING OF HEARTS
Unimportant, of course, I meant.

He says to himself "important — unimportant — unimportant — important —" as if he is trying which word sounds best.

Some of the jury write it down "important," and some "unimportant."

KING OF HEARTS
(at last)
Silence! Rule Forty-two. All persons more than a mile high to leave the court.

Everybody looks at Alice.

ALICE
I'm not a mile high.

KING OF HEARTS
You are.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Nearly two miles high.

ALICE
Well, I shan't go, at any rate. Besides, that's not a regular rule: you invented it just now.

KING OF HEARTS
It's the oldest rule in the book.

ALICE
Then it ought to be Number One.

The King turns pale, and shuts his note-book hastily.

KING OF HEARTS
Consider your verdict.

WHITE RABBIT
There's more evidence to come yet, please your Majesty. This paper has just been picked up.

KING OF HEARTS
What's in it?

WHITE RABBIT
I haven't opened it yet, but it seems to be a letter, written by the prisoner to — to somebody.

KING OF HEARTS
It must have been that, unless it was written to nobody, which isn't usual, you know.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Who is it directed to?

WHITE RABBIT
It isn't directed at all. In fact, there's nothing written on the outside.

He unfolds the paper as he speaks, and adds —

WHITE RABBIT
It isn't a letter, after all: it's a set of verses.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Are they in the prisoner's handwriting?

WHITE RABBIT
No, they're not, and that's the queerest thing about it.

The King is looking very anxiously at the Knave.

KING OF HEARTS
He must have imitated somebody else's hand.

KNAVE OF HEARTS
(spreading out his hands)
Please your Majesty, I didn't write it, and they can't prove I did: there's no name signed at the end.

KING OF HEARTS
If you didn't sign it, that only makes the matter worse. You must have meant some mischief, or else you'd have signed your name like an honest man.

There is a general clapping of hands at this. It is the first really clever thing the King has said that day.

QUEEN OF HEARTS
That proves his guilt.

ALICE
It proves nothing of the sort! Why, you don't even know what they're about!

KING OF HEARTS
Read them.

The White Rabbit puts on his spectacles.

WHITE RABBIT
Where shall I begin, please your Majesty?

KING OF HEARTS
Begin at the beginning, and go on till you come to the end: then stop.

WHITE RABBIT
(reads)
"They told me you had been to her,
And mentioned me to him:
She gave me a good character,
But said I could not swim.

He sent them word I had not gone
(We know it to be true):
If she should push the matter on,
What would become of you?

I gave her one, they gave him two,
You gave us three or more;
They all returned from him to you,
Though they were mine before.

If I or she should chance to be
Involved in this affair,
He trusts to you to set them free,
Exactly as we were.

My notion was that you had been
(Before she had this fit)
An obstacle that came between
Him, and ourselves, and it.

Don't let him know she liked them best,
For this must ever be
A secret, kept from all the rest,
Between yourself and me."

KING OF HEARTS
That's the most important piece of evidence we've heard yet.

ALICE
I don't believe there's an atom of meaning in it.

The jury all write down on their slates, "She doesn't believe there's an atom of meaning in it," but none of them attempt to explain the paper.

KING OF HEARTS
(running his eye over the verses)
If there's no meaning in it, that saves a world of trouble, you know, as we needn't try to find any. And yet I don't know — I seem to see some meaning in them, after all. "— said I could not swim —" you can't swim, can you?

He turns to the Knave.

The Knave shakes his head sadly.

KNAVE OF HEARTS
Do I look like it?

He is made entirely of cardboard, so he cannot possibly swim.

KING OF HEARTS
All right, so far. "We know it to be true" — that's the jury, of course — "I gave her one, they gave him two" — why, that must be what he did with the tarts, you know —

ALICE
But it goes on "they all returned from him to you."

KING OF HEARTS
(triumphantly)
Why, there they are!

He points to the tarts on the table.

ALICE
Nothing of the sort. The words don't fit you at all. You can't even swim, and —

QUEEN OF HEARTS
(furiously)
Sentence first — verdict afterwards.

ALICE
Stuff and nonsense! The idea of having the sentence first!

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Hold your tongue!

ALICE
I won't!

QUEEN OF HEARTS
Off with her head! Off with —

ALICE
(at the top of her voice)
Who cares for you? You're nothing but a pack of cards!

The whole pack rises up into the air, and comes flying down upon her. She gives a little scream, half of fright and half of anger, and tries to beat them off —

EXT. RIVER BANK - DAY

— and finds herself lying on the bank, with her head in the lap of her Sister, who is gently brushing away some dead leaves that have fluttered down from the trees upon her face.

SISTER
Wake up, Alice dear! Why, what a long sleep you've had!

ALICE
Oh, I've had such a curious dream!

She tells her Sister, as well as she can remember them, all these strange Adventures of hers that you have just been reading about. When she has finished, her Sister kisses her and says —

SISTER
It was a curious dream, dear, certainly: but now run in to your tea; it's getting late.

Alice gets up and runs off, thinking while she runs, as well she might, what a wonderful dream it had been.

Her Sister remains sitting on the bank, resting her head on her hand, watching the setting sun, and thinking of little Alice and all her wonderful Adventures, till she too begins dreaming after a fashion.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The Sister sits with her eyes closed, and half believes herself in Wonderland, though she knows she has but to open them again, and all will change to dull reality — the grass rustling in the wind, and the pool rippling to the waving of the reeds — the rattling teacups as the March Hare and his friends share their never-ending meal, and the shrill voice of the Queen ordering off her unfortunate guests to execution — once more the pig-baby is sneezing on the Duchess's knee, while plates and dishes crash around it — once more the shriek of the Gryphon, the squeaking of the Lizard's slate-pencil, and the choking of the suppressed guinea-pigs, filled the air, mixed up with the distant sobs of the miserable Mock Turtle.

She pictures to herself how this same little sister of hers would, in the after-time, be herself a grown woman; and how she would keep, through all her riper years, the simple and loving heart of her childhood; and how she would gather about her other little children, and make their eyes bright and eager with many a strange tale, perhaps even with the dream of Wonderland of long ago; and how she would feel with all their simple sorrows, and find a pleasure in all their simple joys, remembering her own child-life, and the happy summer days.

FADE OUT.

THE END
